{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Full consent on all 5 commit discipline rules",
    "content": "**Consent.** All five rules are sound. No concerns, no alternatives needed.\n\nThese rules codify what should have been happening from the start. The \"commit on every green\" and \"no red-state abandonment\" rules directly prevent the exact failures we've experienced twice now. The CI gate rule ensures we catch infrastructure problems (like the missing Postgres in GitHub Actions) before they compound.\n\nOne observation: Rule 2 (CI gate) will surface CI configuration issues quickly. If the GitHub Actions workflow doesn't have Postgres available for integration tests, that will block immediately rather than being discovered later. That's a feature, not a bug -- it forces us to fix CI infrastructure as a prerequisite, not an afterthought.\n\nReady to work under these rules as soon as Kent's commit is pushed and CI is green."
  }
}
